BTI - GeneReviews(®)
AB  - CLINICAL CHARACTERISTICS: The phenotypic spectrum of untreated glutaric acidemia 
      type 1 (GA1) ranges from severe dystonia due to basal ganglia injury to a variety 
      of other later-onset neurologic manifestations to asymptomatic individuals. The 
      GA1 phenotype can vary widely among untreated family members with the same 
      genotype, primarily as a function of the timing and severity of acute basal 
      ganglia injury. Acute early-onset injury may occur from age three months to three 
      years in infantile-onset GA1 (rarely, up to age six years); more insidious 
      neurologic manifestations may occur after age six years in late-onset GA1. Acute 
      injury manifests as acute bilateral striatal injury and subsequent complex 
      movement disorders. Affected individuals may also develop insidious-onset basal 
      ganglia injury in the absence of an identified acute encephalopathic crisis. 
      Infants identified by newborn screening (NBS) and started on treatment may not 
      develop basal ganglia injury or subsequent movement disorder. Extrastriatal 
      symptoms may occur after age six years including neurologic sequelae such as 
      epilepsy, stroke, and cerebral palsy-like manifestations. DIAGNOSIS/TESTING: The 
      diagnosis of GA1 can be established in a proband with suggestive findings and 
      biallelic pathogenic variants in GCDH identified by molecular genetic testing or 
      significantly reduced glutaryl-CoA dehydrogenase enzyme activity in cultured 
      fibroblasts or leukocytes. MANAGEMENT: Targeted therapies: When GA1 is suspected 
      during the diagnostic evaluation of a newborn with an elevated concentration of 
      3-hydroxyglutaric acid (3-OH-GA) in plasma or urine, metabolic treatment should 
      be initiated immediately, including avoiding catabolism, a low-lysine diet, and 
      carnitine supplementation. Supportive care: Feeding tube as needed; standard 
      therapy for dystonic movement disorders; physical therapy and aggressive 
      rehabilitation therapy for gross motor delay; developmental and educational 
      support; anti-seizure medication per neurologist; education, emergency letter, 
      medical alert bracelet, and dietary supplies to avoid acute encephalopathic 
      crisis; communication prior to surgeries or procedures; transitional care plan. 
      Emergency outpatient treatment includes dietary intervention, antipyretics, and 
      antiemetics. Acute inpatient treatment includes high-energy fluids with insulin 
      as needed, intravenous lipid emulsion, dietary adjustments, seizure medication as 
      needed, and treatment of metabolic acidosis. Surveillance: Regular evaluations by 
      a metabolic specialist and metabolic dietician with quantitative analysis of 
      plasma amino acids; assessment of growth, developmental progress, and educational 
      needs at each visit; neuropsychological testing as needed; assessment for 
      movement disorders at each visit; assessment for nutritional deficiencies if 
      clinically indicated; plasma creatinine and/or cystatin C levels periodically in 
      adolescents and adults; complete blood count, ferritin, alanine transaminase, 
      aspartate transaminase, and albumin if clinically indicated; consider head MRI if 
      clinically indicated; assessment of quality of life and family needs as needed. 
      Agents/circumstances to avoid: Excessive dietary protein or protein malnutrition 
      inducing catabolic state; prolonged fasting; catabolic illness (intercurrent 
      infection; brief febrile illness post vaccination); inadequate caloric provision 
      during other stressors (e.g., surgery or procedure requiring fasting/anesthesia); 
      avoidance or extreme caution with contact sports and physical activity that 
      increase the risk for head injury. Evaluation of relatives at risk: If prenatal 
      testing has not been performed, a newborn with an older sib with GA1 should be 
      treated at birth pending results of the definitive glutaryl-CoA dehydrogenase 
      enzyme activity assay and/or molecular genetic testing (if the GCDH pathogenic 
      variants in the family are known). The genetic status of older sibs (even if 
      asymptomatic) of a child with GA1 should be clarified by assay of glutaryl-CoA 
      dehydrogenase enzyme activity or molecular genetic testing so that treatment can 
      be instituted in a timely manner. Pregnancy management: It is recommended that 
      care for a pregnant woman with GA1 be provided by a multidisciplinary team 
      including the treating obstetrician, a metabolic physician, and a specialist 
      metabolic dietician. GENETIC COUNSELING: GA1 is inherited in an autosomal 
      recessive manner. If both parents are known to be heterozygous for a GCDH 
      pathogenic variant, each sib of an affected individual has at conception a 25% 
      chance of being affected, a 50% chance of being an asymptomatic carrier, and a 
      25% chance of being unaffected and not a carrier. Once the GCDH pathogenic 
      variants have been identified in an affected family member, carrier testing for 
      at-risk relatives and prenatal/preimplantation genetic testing are possible.
